      "In almost every class there are one or two children for whom reading is a genuine, daily struggle — not laziness, not lack of trying, but real difficulty. How the adults around them respond shapes not only their reading but their whole relationship with learning and their sense of themselves. Handled with skill and care, a struggling reader can make real progress and keep their confidence; handled with pressure and public exposure, they can learn to hate reading and to feel stupid, which is far harder to undo than any decoding gap.",
