      "## Protect dignity first",
      "The single most damaging classroom practice for a struggling reader is public exposure — being made to read aloud, cold, in front of peers who read easily. The humiliation attaches itself to reading itself, and a child who feels shamed will avoid the very practice they most need. Skilled teachers protect these children: they never spring cold reading on them, they let them prepare a passage privately before reading it aloud, and they find ways for the child to participate and succeed publicly at things they can do.",
      "Confidence is not a soft extra here; it is load-bearing. A struggling reader who still believes they can improve will keep trying, and trying is the whole engine of progress. One who has decided they are \"bad at reading\" has stopped, and the reading stops with them.",
      "## Meet them where they are",
      "Progress comes from reading at the right level — texts that stretch a little but do not overwhelm — not from grinding through material far too hard. High-interest, lower-difficulty books are gold: they let a struggling reader engage with content that feels age-appropriate and exciting without a punishing decoding load. Plenty of reading at a comfortable level builds the fluency that unlocks everything else, so volume at the right level beats difficulty every time.",
      "Structured, systematic support for the specific gaps — often in the sounds-and-letters foundations — helps many struggling readers, and the earlier the better. Small, frequent, focused sessions generally beat occasional long ones. And celebrating concrete progress, however small, keeps the motivation that everything depends on alive.",
      "## Partnership, not blame",
      "Struggling readers are best served when home and school pull together rather than pointing fingers. Teachers can share specific, doable strategies with parents; parents can keep home reading pressure-free and positive, reading aloud for pleasure and letting the child experience books above their own level. Neither should let reading become a nightly battle, because a child who dreads reading practice will get less from it than one who does a little, happily.",
      "Above all, both should hold and communicate the belief that the child can improve — because they usually can, with the right level of text, the right targeted help, protected dignity, and patience. A struggling reader is not a failing child; they are a child who needs a different, kinder, more precise kind of support. Given it, most of them get there.",
